Creating images with R

with a little bit of magick

Tim Cross

March 13 2023

My meme

My meme is a spin on the whisper / hair rising meme, with the caption “Mum’s got the slow cooker on.” This is an original meme, as recently there have been a number of “memes” on social media platforms throwing off at slow cookers. I personally love my Mum’s slow cooker and decided to put a positive spin on it.

#Reading in magick package
library(magick)

#Loading in  top half of the meme and attaching text 
tophalf <- image_read(path = "Images/TopHalf.png") %>%  
  image_annotate(text = "Mum's got the\n slow cooker on",
                 color = "#ffd700",
                 size = 90,
                 gravity = "South",
                 font = "Arial")

image_blank(0,0)

#Loading in bottom half of the meme
bothalf <- image_read(path = "Images/BottomHalf.png")

#Stacking both the top half and bottom of the image on top of each other
Meme <- image_append(c(tophalf, bothalf), stack = TRUE)

#Creating a png
image_write(Meme, "Finalmeme.png")

My animated GIF

My gif is a countdown of 3, 2, 1 and then a photo of a quokka - a very cute Australian animal with the caption “smile”. With countdown-style gifs, often the images are inappropriate or offensive, this is certainly not one of those. This gif is designed to make people smile, even if you’re having a tough day. The use of the quokka is also very original, I had an intersnhip in Australia over summer and first heard about these cute animals then and hope this meme shows more people these adorable animals.

#Reading in magick package
library(magick)

gif_image <- image_read(path = "Smile.png") %>%
  image_scale(500)

# creating each frame, where the text comes from the counts vector
frame1 <- image_blank(color = "white", width = 500, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = 5, size = 100, gravity = "center", weight = 500)

frame2 <- image_blank(color = "white", width = 500, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = 4, size = 100, gravity = "center", weight = 500)

frame3 <- image_blank(color = "white", width = 500, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = 3, size = 100, gravity = "center", weight = 500)

frame4 <- image_blank(color = "white", width = 500, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = 2, size = 100, gravity = "center", weight = 500)

frame5 <- image_blank(color = "white", width = 500, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = 1, size = 100, gravity = "center", weight = 500)

frame6 <- gif_image %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Smile", size = 100, gravity = "south", col = "yellow", weight = 800)

# putting the frames in order using a vector
frames <- c(frame1, frame2, frame3, frame4, frame5, frame6)

# creating an animation
animation <- image_animate(frames, fps = 1)

#saving my image as a gif
image_write(animation, "my_animation.gif")
